      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1544533535,
      "post_id" : 41385460,
      "comment_id" : 94302894,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "In Java 8 you can easily convert an <code>Iterator</code> back to a <b>single use</b> <code>Iterable</code> by using <code>() -&gt; iterator</code>. This can be useful in situations like this, but let me stress the important thing again: You can use this method only if a <b>single use</b> <code>Iterable</code> is acceptable. Calling <code>iterable.iterator()</code> more than once will yield unexpected results. The above answer then becomes <code>Iterator&lt;Element&gt; iterator = createIterator();</code> <code>List&lt;Element&gt; array = StreamSupport.stream(((Iterable&lt;Element&gt;) () -&gt; iterable).spliterator(), false).collect(toList());</code>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6674768,
      "reputation" : 542,
      "user_id" : 5149824,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b3f1f6f1a9f88f5debeac984cd0c9d89?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Dub Nazar",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5149824/dub-nazar"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 32,
    "last_activity_date" : 1536246812,
    "last_edit_date" : 1536246812,
    "creation_date" : 1483037044,
    "answer_id" : 41385460,
    "question_id" : 10117026,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Note there is a difference between <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Iterable.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Iterable</code></a> and <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Iterator.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Iterator</code></a>.</p>\n\n<p>If you have an <strong><code>Iterable</code></strong>, then with Java 8 you can use this solution:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Iterable&lt;Element&gt; iterable = createIterable();\nList&lt;Element&gt; array = StreamSupport\n    .stream(iterable.spliterator(), false)\n    .collect(Collectors.toList());\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>As I know <code>Collectors.toList()</code> creates <code>ArrayList</code> instance.</p>\n\n<p>Actually in my opinion, it also looks good in one line.<br>\nFor example if you need to return <code>List&lt;Element&gt;</code> from some method:</p>\n\n<pre><code>return StreamSupport.stream(iter.spliterator(), false).collect(Collectors.toList());\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
